## examples
1. Let $G_1 = \left\{ e_1,a_1 \right\}$ with $a_1^2 = e_1$ and $G_2 = \left\{ e_2,a_2 \right\}$ with $a_2^2 = e_2$
since the cardinality of the group is 4, it is isomorphic to the kliens_four group or $\mathbb{Z}_4$. Recall that $\mathbb{Z}_4 =\left<b \right>$ with $b^{4}=e$ then $\mathbb{Z}_4 = \left\{ e, b, b^2, b^3 \right\}$, $\left| e \right| =1, \left| b \right| =4,\left| b^2 \right|=2, \left| b^3 \right| = 4$ (since 3 and 4 are coprime), Returning to $G_1\times G_2$ all of its elements are of the form: $\left( a_1^{n},a_2^{m} \right)$. $\left( a_1^{n},a_2^{m} \right)^2 =\left( a_1^{2n},a_2^{2m} \right) = \left( e_1,e_2 \right)$.

All non-identity elements in $G_1\times G_2$ have order $2$. $G_1\times G_2$ is not isomorphic to $Z_4$ as the elements order should be preserved

So it must be isomorphic to $G_1\times G_2 \equiv V_4$

2. $\mathbb{Z}_2 \times \mathbb{Z}_3 \equiv \mathbb{Z}_6$ with elements $(a,b)$ with $a \in \left\{ 0,1 \right\}, b \left\{ 0,1,2 \right\}$. If we find an element that generates $\mathbb{Z}_2 \times  \mathbb{Z}_3$, this would be the first question you should ask, since it makes life a lot easier. It is clear that $(1,1)$ generates, since 2, and 3 are coprime. 

